PRINTF(3)                  Library Functions Manual                 PRINTF(3)

NAME
       _printf - print text and variables in a formatted way

SYNOPSIS
       #include "main.h"

       int _printf(const char *format, ...);

DESCRIPTION
       The _printf() function is a simplified version of the C library printf.
       It sends output to the standard output (your screen).

       The format string can contain:
        - Normal characters: they are printed exactly as they are.
        - Special format codes starting with %: these are replaced with values
          from the extra arguments that follow.

       Supported format codes in this project are:
              %c   Print a single character.
              %s   Print a string (prints "(null)" if the string is NULL).
              %%   Print a literal percent sign.
              %d   Print a signed decimal integer.
              %i   Print a signed decimal integer (same as %d).

RETURN VALUE
       On success, _printf() returns the number of characters printed.
       On error, it returns -1.

EXAMPLES
       The following program demonstrates the use of each specifier.

           #include "main.h"

           /**
            * main - Entry Point
            *
            * Return: Always 0
            */
           int main(void)
           {
               /* Print a character */
               _printf("Character: %c\n", 'A');

               /* Print a string */
               _printf("String: %s\n", "Hello");

               /* Print an integer */
               _printf("Integer: %d\n", 123);

               /* Print a number in binary */
               _printf("Binary of 98: %b\n", 98);

               /* Print a percent sign */
               _printf("Percent: %%\n");

               return (0);
           }

BUGS
       This implementation of _printf() does not handle flag characters,
       field width, precision, or length modifiers.

SEE ALSO
       printf(3), write(2), stdarg(3)

